<h1>From Bryan Fairfax</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Alexandria May the 21st 1774.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>We have obtained a Judgement vs. Doctor Savage for the whole Sum that we expected, amounting to 600, and upwards. I have since spoke to Doctor Savage on the Matter. He now proposes to leave the Affair to Arbitration, alledging the Equity he might have in a Court of Chancery on Account of the Deed of Relinquishment entered into or executed by Mrs Savage before she left Virginia.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I have told him that my opinion was that we had no Right so to do. However having promised to write to You to know your Sentiments I shall be glad to be informed of them, and also your opinion as to what is next proper to be done. He intimates that the Affair may Still be long before it is
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-10-02-pb-0067">[67]</span>
determined as he has it or will have it in his Power to appeal,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> and offers to pay the Annuity from the Time that Mrs Savage left his House in Ireland, and to settle an Annuity in Rents for the future. This Letter being intended only for this Business, I shall only add that I am Dr Sir Yr most obedt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Bryan Fairfax</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0050-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For an overall view of the Savage affair, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0342&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-07-02-0342-fn-0001#GEWN-02-07-02-0342-fn-0001" class="document">Henry Lee and Daniel Payne to GW, 24 April 1767, n.1</a>. For the deed of relinquishment signed by Margaret Savage, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0080" class="document">GW to Margaret Savage, 28 June 1768</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0080&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0080-fn-0002#GEWN-02-08-02-0080-fn-0002" class="document">note 2</a> of that document.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0050-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Dr. Savage did appeal the case, but both principals died without a final decision being reached.</p>

</div>
